                <fr:title text="Noetherian and locally Noetherian schemes">Noetherian and locally Noetherian schemes</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  We say a scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>locally Noetherian</html:em>, if it can be covered by affine subspaces <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> with each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/idem-comm-JOTR/" title="Noetherian distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-JOTR/" display-uri="idem-comm-JOTR" type="local">Noetherian</fr:link>. Equivalently by <fr:link href="/schm-KSRJ/" title="Noetherian condition is affine local" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-KSRJ/" display-uri="schm-KSRJ" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-KSRJ/" display-uri="schm-KSRJ" /></fr:link>, every affine open is Noetherian. We say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>Noetherian</html:em> if it is furthermore <fr:link href="/schm-H9PK/" title="Quasi-compact and quasi-separated schemes" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-H9PK/" display-uri="schm-H9PK" type="local">quasi-compact</fr:link>.
</html:p>
